{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is real git rename detection plus CLI parsing/output. A Unit test of rename parsing alone is too low because the bug can be in git invocation flags (for example, rename detection not enabled), which only appears with real git subprocess/repo interaction (REAL-INFRA, MOCK-HIDE). Integration was considered, but behavior text requires actual repository changes being analyzed, so higher level is not disqualified.","test_description":"Create a temporary real git repo, commit a file, rename it with content similarity preserved, run the CLI as a subprocess, and assert the report increments only the renamed category (not added/deleted) for that change set.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The real failure often comes from subprocess output/encoding and git’s binary diff behavior, not pure local logic. Mocked diff text can miss real byte/format edge cases (REAL-INFRA, MOCK-HIDE). Integration was considered, but behavior text explicitly ties to real diffs including binary files, which is best exercised through git subprocess output.","test_description":"In a temporary git repo, add/modify a real binary file (for example random bytes), run the CLI subprocess over the relevant range, assert exit code is success and binary file contributes to counts without traceback/crash.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.67,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This depends on unborn-HEAD git behavior and subprocess exit handling. Unit/Integration fakes can simulate errors but may miss actual git error modes/messages and return codes for empty-history repos (REAL-INFRA, MOCK-HIDE). Higher levels (Agentic/Workflow) are disqualified because no AI/ML output or multi-agent sequencing is involved.","test_description":"Initialize a new git repo with no commits, execute the CLI subprocess from that repo, and assert successful execution with an empty structured report on stdout.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.83,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is an end-to-end correctness claim against real repository history. The failure can arise from git command selection, revision range semantics, and parser aggregation across real subprocess outputs. In-process module wiring alone is insufficient to guarantee catching these failures (REAL-INFRA, MOCK-HIDE). Agentic/Workflow are disqualified: no model-dependent output.","test_description":"Build a temp repo with a known sequence of commits containing added/deleted/renamed/modified files, run the CLI subprocess over that history, and assert each reported count matches the known ground truth from the constructed commit sequence.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.86,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior depends on real git index vs working-tree semantics, which are OS/subprocess-backed states. Mocked/stubbed calls can hide differences in how staged and unstaged changes are surfaced by git commands (REAL-INFRA, MOCK-HIDE). Integration was considered, but behavior text explicitly compares staged vs unstaged repository states, requiring real git behavior.","test_description":"In a temp git repo, create equivalent change sets once as staged and once as unstaged, run the CLI subprocess in both states, and assert byte-for-byte identical structured stdout output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
